A black box in your car?
While U.S. road network planners are struggling to find the money to repair the declining highway infrastructure, many are seeing a solution in the form of a small black box that attaches itself above the dashboard of your car.
The aircraft, which record every mile traveled by a motorist and pass on the information to officials, are at the center of a controversial attempt in Washington and in government planning offices to reshape the outdated funding system of major American roads.
The generally uninteresting sector of major-axis planning has suddenly provoked a heated debate and busy alliances.
Libertarians joined environmental groups to pressure the government to use small boxes to keep track of the miles you travel, and possibly the road you travel, and then use the information to draft a tax bill.
The tea party has landed.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also very concerned and expresses concern about privacy.
And while members of Congress can’t agree on whether to continue, several states haven’t waited.
They are looking at how, over the next decade, they will be able to move to a system that allows drivers to pay based on the number of miles traveled.
Thousands of drivers have already boarded these black boxes, sometimes equipped with a GPS monitoring system, for an experimental ride.
This is truly indispensable for our nation.
“It’s not like we have a choice,” said Hasan Ikhrata, managing director of the Southern California Association of Governments, which predicts that the state will start recording miles traveled by every California driver by 2025.
There will be a change in the way we pay these taxes.
Technology is here to do it.
The pressure comes from the fact that the country’s Highway Trust Fund, funded by taxes Americans pay at the pump, is financially dry.
Americans don't buy as much gasoline as they used to.
Cars can travel more than a gallon.
The federal tax itself, which is 18.4 cents per gallon, has not increased in 20 years.
Politicians are reluctant to raise the tax even by 1 cent, while gasoline prices are high.
"The gas tax is simply not sustainable," said Lee Munnich, a transportation policy specialist at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently had tracers installed on 500 cars to test a mile-by-mile payment system.
“This turns out to be the most logical long-term alternative,” he said.
Wonks calls this a mileage usage fee.
It is not surprising that the idea appeals to urban liberals, as taxes could be used to change driving habits in ways that reduce congestion and gas emissions, for example.
California planners are interested in the system as they develop strategies to achieve the goals set in the state’s ambitious global warming laws.
But Representative Bill Shuster (R-Pa.), chairman of the House Transportation Committee, said he also considered it the most viable long-term alternative.
Reason Foundation free market supporters also appreciate the idea of paying drivers on the mile.
“It’s not just a tax going into a big black hole,” said Adrian Moore, vice president of politics at the Reason Foundation.
People pay more directly for the benefits they receive.
The move is also supported by two former U.S. transportation secretaries who, in a 2011 report, urged Congress to go on the mileage path.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would cover about 10,000 cars.
But the House presidency killed the proposal, responding to the concerns of rural lawmakers representing voters who have to travel many miles every day to get to their work or to the city.
Nevertheless, several states and major cities are making progress on their side.
The most determined is Oregon, which has mobilized 5,000 drivers to conduct the country's most important experience.
These drivers will soon pay the state mileage charges instead of gasoline taxes.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
The city of New York is considering one.
Illinois is attempting a trial on a limited number of trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes 17 agencies involved in road transport in states along the U.S. East Coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida) is studying how it could implement the change.
The concept is not a universal success.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer drivers recently equipped their cars with an aircraft, drivers were worried that the government could follow their slightest actions.
“The concerns about Big Brother and things like that are a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, who heads strategic performance management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
This is not something that people want.
At the start of the test, the Nevada ACLU warned on its site, "It would be relatively easy to turn these devices into full-fledged tracking devices."
There is no need to build a huge and cumbersome technological infrastructure that will inevitably be expanded to keep records of people’s daily goings and comings.
Nevada is among the few states that are now struggling to find affordable technology that would let the state know how many miles a car travels, but without knowing the exact location or time.
If we can do that, Khan added, the citizens will be more comfortable.
Research into this technology has led some state agencies to call on a small California startup named True Mileage.
Originally, the company was not meant to help motorists paying taxes to states.
It was looking to break into the emerging car insurance market, where drivers would pay based on their mileage.
But the devices she is testing have pleased the planners of the major axes because they do not use GPS and provide a limited amount of information, downloaded periodically by modem.
“People will be more likely to do that if you don’t record their speed and locate them,” said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
Major errors have been made in the pilot programmes of some States.
There are much less expensive ways and much less intrusive methods to proceed.
In Oregon, planners try the experience by offering motorists different choices.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
They can still choose not to have a device at all, preferring instead to pay a package based on the average number of miles traveled by all state residents.
Other states hope to sell the concept to suspicious citizens by allowing devices to do more, rather than not enough.
In New York City, transportation officials are looking to develop a tax system that would also be equipped to pay parking fees, provide “pay-to-drive” insurance, and create a set of real-time speed data from other drivers that drivers could use to avoid traffic jams.
"Drivers would be encouraged to participate because of the benefits that the system offers them," said an urban planning document.
However, some transport planners are wondering if the entire debate on mileage is not simply a huge diversion.
At the San Francisco Bay Area Metropolitan Transportation Commission, officials say Congress could very simply manage the bankruptcy of the Highway Trust Fund by raising taxes on gasoline.
An additional one-time or annual tax could be imposed on drivers of hybrid vehicles and others whose vehicles do not consume much gasoline, so that everyone pays their fair share.
“There is no need for radical surgery when you simply need aspirin,” said Randy Rentschler, the commission’s director of legislation and public affairs.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of motorists will worry about protecting their privacy and a lot of other things.
