George Kerevan: The breakup of Europe gives Scots a choice
Another day, another worrying story of independence.
This time, we are being warned that an independent Scotland would be required to join the European free movement zone in order to be able to join the EU.
And now we hear stories of passport control in Berwick and a border of barbed wire along Hadrian's wall.
While it is true that the Strathclyde newspaper indicated the possible economic benefits of greater freedom of movement with the rest of Europe, this was not in the headlines (and was to be expected).
Neither did anyone say that the EU member states spend a lot of their time circumventing their formal rules when they are arranged.
Since Scotland is not part of the Schengen area at the moment, continued non-compliance with the rules would be a thin concession that Brussels could offer in return for everything it wants from the Scots.
This is a story that is not one.
And a story so old that it is now frozen: I first heard the bummer that “independence means passport control” more than 40 years ago.
Yet one interesting point has been forgotten in this interpretation of an old dusty tale.
Why should an independent Scotland actually follow Europe’s instructions?
Why exchange the yoke of London for that of Brussels, especially now?
Here is the real news about Europe: the great post-war plan to unify Europe is definitely at a standstill.
With the euro crisis, Project Europe is officially dead.
Across Europe, parties opposing the EU or advocating the abandonment of the euro as a common currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party, founded only this year and arrived from nowhere, gathered almost five million votes in the federal elections in September and removed the Liberal Democratic Party (equivalent to our Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been a national opposition to the plan to create a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis has marked a turning point.
The austerity imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, coupled with the scourge on national economies through accession to the single currency, has led many people to think that Project Europe has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments that have excessive budget deficits – this was only true for Greece.
Rather, the European system has imposed on its members exchange rates favorable to German exporters – which German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of a devaluation of the national currency, the countries of southern Europe find themselves with an intrinsic productivity problem vis-<0xC3><0xA0>-vis Germany.
The only remedy is to make dark cuts in wages and public spending – encouraged by Berlin.
Beyond the current fiscal and monetary problems, there is a deeper discomfort related to productivity in Europe.
Following the “green” energy policies imposed by Brussels – which are a reason to subsidize French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers – the European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas as the United States.
This is a downside in terms of costs, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
All wage freezes in the world will not prevent the European petrochemical industry from being penalized by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, the revolt is raging, especially in France, one of the EU’s major leaders.
After the war, the French political elite considered the EU as a way to control Germany and put Paris on an equal footing with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a passport of its political legitimacy and has imposed its own economic policy in Europe, leaving the French economy in trouble.
As a result, Marine Le Pen’s far-right party, the anti-European National Front, has just won a crucial by-election, returning the Socialists to power in third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France with 24% of the vote – a timely warning for the British Labour Party that it cannot assume that a split from the right will automatically favor the left.
What does Marine Le Pen do with her new popularity with the French white working class?
It wants to use next year’s European elections to create a single, anti-European currency bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-European parties do well in these elections, which is very possible, such a bloc could control the European Parliament for the first time.
This is what I think: very soon, the anti-European and anti-currency sentiment in Europe will unify and eventually kill the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will return to something that will look more like the "Europe of Nations (sovereign)" privileged free by General de Gaulle.
Germany and some of its satellite economies could retain the euro, but France and Southern Europe will find their own currency.
I expect the United Kingdom to distance itself from this project, and I hope it will be gentle on the United States.
However, Washington's growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be left behind in the Atlantic.
What about Scotland in all this?
We can decide to be a region of small England (essentially).
Or we can defend our own economic interests, which includes sending around Berlin and Brussels.
I believe that Scotland could accommodate a freer European agreement provided we keep our own currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries would be easier in a non-federal Europe of Nations.
Otherwise, we should imitate Norway and maintain our economic independence.
The SNP government of Scotland is – and it should be noted – the most successful anti-austerity political movement in Europe, as it won a dramatic majority in 2011 based on its opposition to the dark cuts proposed (and implemented) by the Labour Chancellor, Alistair Darling, and the Conservative/Liberal Democratic coalition who followed.
