Early Puberty: Aging Early
Studies show that African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than white girls.
Physical changes do not mean puberty is imminent
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible.
Experts believe obesity epidemic could be a trigger for early puberty
The trend towards early puberty is not as pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in family and child health issues.
Should a mother worry if her daughter’s breasts and pubic hair start to grow at age 7 or 8?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics held this week in Orlando, Florida, pedo-endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these early physical changes are fairly common among young American women and represent a new norm.
“I spend a lot of time reassuring parents – in general, this does not indicate a rapid shift towards full puberty,” Kaplowitz said.
Obvious signs of development, such as budding breasts, hair under the arms and in the pubic area, and body odors, appear earlier in girls.
But there has been only a slight advance in the age of first menstruation over the past four decades.
In the United States, the average age is 12 and a half years, compared to 12 years three-quarters in 1970.
"Once the breast has started to develop, it takes at least two or three years before the first menstrual periods appear," Kaplowitz, also the author of Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Coping with This Common Problem, said in a statement.
Time is the most accurate test for how puberty will evolve.
There is a debate about what constitutes the actual onset of puberty, but it is considered "early" when breast development is accompanied by sudden growth before the age of 8.
In most cases, development slows down or stops – this is something a pediatrician can follow closely.
A faster evolution may justify tests performed by an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are treatments to delay the onset of the first menstruation and prevent other consequences: premature aging of the bones that can slow growth and small size in adulthood.
Recommendations for drug and hormone treatment are based on the child's age, rate of development, rate of growth and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious about drugs but acknowledges that "controlling puberty can alleviate certain behavioral problems and the feeling for young girls to be different from others."
The other big problem is understandable: Parents simply don’t want their very young girls to have their periods.
“They fear the risk of pregnancy or even how they will handle hygiene issues,” Kaplowitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls a woman whose daughter had her first menstrual period at the age of 10.
Even though there were signs and we had talked about the rules, she wasn’t emotionally prepared.
She returned from school frightened and upset to be the first among her friends.
There are many theories brought to the public about the causes of early puberty.
Yet there is no consistent theory that the hormones contained in milk or other foods, chemicals present in the environment, or sexual messages conveyed by the media are responsible.
Boys, like girls, reach puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz says the most credible hypothesis is the obesity epidemic.
He participated in a study in girls aged 6 to 9 years that links the percentage of fat mass to the onset of puberty.
Other findings support this conclusion, but there are many other influential factors.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than white girls.
There are various explanations.
Globally, the mechanisms of early puberty seem to be influenced by everything from economic conditions to climate and genes.
Another problem: Although boys have younger hair on the face and in the pubic area, the trend towards real early puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors attending the AAP conference stressed the complexity of the topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is common, even in infants and toddlers.
“We need to be cautious about how we identify the true onset of puberty,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a paedo-endocrinologist working at Goryeb Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to ask their pediatrician for advice on how to talk to their child.
“It may mean having a conversation earlier than expected,” Kaplowitz said.
If you stay calm, your child will react well in general.
Girls with early puberty should be reassured that even when it happens earlier than expected, the process is part of life.
