How Biometrics Will Invade Our Lives
Don’t have your passwords typed to access your smartphone or pay for your purchases?
American, French or Japanese researchers predict a future where we will be recognized by the biometric sensors of phones and computers.
Bernard Didier, deputy general manager of Morpho, even believes that "the century will be biometric".
Only biometrics will make it possible to ascertain the identity of a person making transactions in a universe as transversal and transnational as the Internet.
Privacy organizations confirm this enthusiasm for biometrics, but are concerned about it.
In 2011 alone and in France, the Commission Nationale de l’Informatique et des Libertés authorized 774 systems for the recognition of fingerprints, the shape of the hand or the venous network of the hand in companies, administrations, canteens...
“Everyone will soon be able to be identified, anywhere, anytime,” said Justin Brookman, head of consumer privacy at the Center for Democracy and Technology (CDT) in Washington.
The reasons for such optimism, in some, and pessimism, in others?
Biometrics will be based on new technologies that will provide new services to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most commonly used biometric data are fingerprints, the contour of the hand and the venous network of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its constraints.
"For example, some people who work in concrete have very damaged fingers and their fingerprints are unreadable," says Philippe Robin, Technical Director of Identity at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection as well as the verification of the venous network and the contour of the hand presuppose a voluntary and precise gesture of the people.
It is both a security - this data cannot be captured without their knowledge - and a drawback: sometimes the procedure has to be repeated and therefore takes time.
Consequently, research has been carried out for about twenty years on other approaches, such as facial recognition or the iris (the colored part of the eye).
Thanks to the increased accuracy of sensors and the computational capacity of computers required for data analysis, these techniques become operational.
The accuracy of facial recognition has increased tenfold over the past five years, calculates Cyrille Bataller, director of Accenture’s R&D laboratories in Europe.
With our help, the UK and Holland deployed automatic border crossings using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
“Today, we’re conducting research on voice recognition or how to walk with sound sensors, but we need a quiet environment,” said Sridhar Iyengar, director of security research at Intel Labs.
As a unique and unmistakable marker, DNA also raises hopes and concerns.
"In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered as the ultimate biometric data," confirms Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, Director of Studies, Innovation and Foresight at the CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC offers the police a suitcase costing 90,000 euros to analyze DNA samples at the scene of a crime and in an hour.
The uses of biometrics are divided into two groups: identification (recognizing one person among others) and authentication (ensuring that the person is who they claim to be).
Until now, identification has been about the issuance of identity documents: biometrics (prints, photographs, irises) must be compared with the information that the State has on all citizens already registered.
This helps to ensure that a person is not trying to impersonate someone else.
This principle of comparison may have other applications.
NEC offers VIP recognition at the entrance of a hotel or shop.
“We retrieve images from surveillance cameras and compare them to photos of celebrities who circulate freely on the Internet,” said Dany Nassif, NEC France’s business development manager for biometric identification solutions.
Another use: take a photo of a quidam who queues in a store, track its progress thanks to facial recognition and calculate the waiting time.
Authentication initially involved physical access (borders, protected premises, canteens...) or logical access (opening a computer).
More recently, presence control has been added.
"A biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of the boyfriend pointing for another," explains Cyrille Bataller, of Accenture.
Increasingly, however, authentication will also concern transactions, in particular those made from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from some distributors by introducing his card and placing his hand on a biometric reader: this gesture replaces the keying of the secret code.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoulême by the company Natural Security in partnership with banks and retailers: when paying in store with his credit card, the customer does not type his code, but inserts his finger in a reader that scans the veins.
The experiment is scheduled to last six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon arrive at French traders.
Ways to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometrics appealing to the general public.
The first is to explain that it can save time.
"If, thanks to biometrics, a customer stays in the box thirty seconds less, it is appreciable," explains the director of a large area.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you custom options.
And finally, reassure by highlighting the precautions taken to protect databases.
“Fingerprints are stored on a first server; people’s identities are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure box, which crashes if you try to move it,” Philippe Robin of Thales enumerates.
But in the absence of in-depth studies, it is impossible to know if these discourses really convince users.
Privacy experts, however, continue to be concerned.
“The advances in facial recognition, the proliferation of surveillance cameras and the huge amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa, make me fear the worst: widespread surveillance,” said Andrew Patrick, the Canadian Privacy Commissioner.
