Scientists have just highlighted how the movements of a dog’s tail are related to his mood.
Previous studies had found that happy dogs moved their tails more to the right (from the dog’s point of view), while nervous dogs moved it more to the left.
But now scientists say dogs can detect these subtle differences and respond to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: “Everyone knows that in humans, the left side and the right side of the brain are differently involved in stimuli that awaken positive or negative emotions.”
Here, we tried to see what was happening to other species.
He added that just as in humans, in dogs, the right side of the brain was responsible for movement to the left and vice versa, and that both hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to disordered tail movements from other dogs, researchers followed animals watching movies that featured other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behavior.
It will surely not take long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes to one side and sometimes to the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: “We introduced dogs to films that featured other dogs – either a naturalistic version or a silhouette to avoid any other confusion – and we were able to smuggle the tail movement and present it as going more left or right.”
When the animals saw an expressionless dog waving the tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog waving the tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they spotted a tail deviating mainly to the left (again from the dog's perspective moving the tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think that dogs deliberately communicate with each other through these movements.
Instead, he thinks that dogs know from experience the movements they should or shouldn’t worry about.
“If you meet other dogs repeatedly and notice that, most of the time, the movement of their tail to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and the right side results in a less friendly attitude, you will react based on that experience.”
The researchers indicate that the results could allow owners, vets and trainers to better understand the emotions of their animals.
Canine behavior expert John Bradshaw, a visiting professor at the University of Bristol's School of Veterinary Science, said this was not the first study to examine the importance of left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team at Lincoln University discovered that dogs turned their heads to the left when they looked at an aggressive dog and to the right when it was a happy dog.
And in another scientific study conducted by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: “Dogs would be easier to go to a robot dog when its tail moved to the left rather than to the right, instead of becoming anxious – the opposite of what is in the Italian study.”
He said the differences could come from the fact that the dogs that participated in the different studies did not fully regard the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study on how dogs react to real dogs could be helpful, he explained.
“While many evidence from different mammals indicates that both sides of the brain are being used for different purposes, many details still need to be clarified – and dogs are no exception,” he said.
However, given the ease with which their behaviors can be recorded, it will surely not take long before we understand why their tail sometimes moves on one side and sometimes on the other.
