A team of biologists led by the New York Wildlife Conservation Society has identified a new species of humping dolphin off the northern coast of Australia.
Thibaut Bouveroux, Scientific Mission Officer at the Observatory for Conservation and the Study of Animals and Marine Environments (OCEAMM) returns to L'Express on this discovery and explains the long process of identifying new species.
Does the discovery of this new species of humping dolphin surprise you?
This is good news, but I am not particularly surprised.
While species have been described and identified in the past on a morphological, anatomical and geographical basis, today the development of new tools such as genetics allows us to improve our knowledge in the sciences of species classification.
Moreover, it is not impossible for these advances in genetics and molecular biology to call into question the classification or belonging of a species to a genus, a family, or even an order.
In the early 19th century, morphologists classified animals, based on morphological differences between species.
Today, some of these rankings are challenged due to advances in genetics.
In the same way, two very morphologically close species have been distinguished thanks to genetics.
This is the case with the new species that has just been identified.
About a decade ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this sub-family: Pacific humpback dolphins and Atlantic humpback whales.
Recent analyses have distinguished four species.
Why is this an important discovery as claimed by the Wildlife Conservation Society?
From a conservation point of view, it is essential to know these genetic differences, in order to protect the species and therefore its genetic variability.
If this population had been known to researchers for a long time, they did not know that it was part of a new species, only present at this location.
Therefore, if a problem of mass mortality caused by a viral epidemic or accidental capture arises in the region, we could be dealing with the extinction of a species, rather than a local extinction of a population of a species more widespread on Earth.
This loss of genetic heritage would be much more problematic.
A species is considered threatened or endangered depending on the number of individuals existing on Earth, i.e. the stock, and the possibility it has to recover from neighboring stocks.
With respect to the Sousa chinensis species, from which the population of the newly discovered species is derived, its stock has automatically become weaker, thus making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are located at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogeneous, open habitats where there is a lot of genetic exchange between populations and individuals.
This breeding of genes limits the creation of new species.
Conversely, more closed ecosystems promote genetic isolation, which can eventually lead to the creation of new species.
The marine environment is the least well-known.
It is better to send robots to Mars than to know what lives in the Mariana pit, just 11 kilometers from the surface of the sea.
We spend more money on the search for life on other planets than on marine research and it is high time that that changes.
