Back in black and white for Marie Chouinard, who presents to Danse Danse her two new group choreographies: the first inspired by the inks and poems of Henri Michaux, the second inspired by Satie’s famous piano solos Gymnopédies.
An evening that allows to see all the prism of Chouinard, from art to tics and from black ink to white.
A white screen serves as a background wall.
On the carpet, as white, in the immense space that is the Thé<0xC3><0xA2>tre Maisonneuve, advances, profiled, thin as a line and dressed in black, a body.
On the screen, an ink by Henri Michaux is projected.
The body, simple line, takes its form.
And this form will be that of the whole piece: a row of physical imitations of drawings.
The dancers, fully dressed in black, with only their hands and face uncovered, wait on either side of the playground, rush when the next graphic appears, embody it, come out running.
This black and white play by Henri Michaux is done in solo relays, in a group in unison (a mass that makes solo), in a large group of twelve solos where each performs his sign.
We think of "Gloire du morgne", where, in solo, Chouinard performed a series of choreographic tasks written on cartels, posed online at the forefront.
This is the same principle, giant PowerPoint version.
Here, the music is loud, percussion and electric guitars.
The energy is high, the pace is always fast.
There will be breakage when Carol Prieur takes refuge under the dance mat, to deliver, microphone in hand, without sobriety or restraint, a portion of Michaux's poem, monocord and monotonous in the crie, and will continue dancing.
And the music to go back, and the sequence to resume.
This sound and energetic discharge, long, if possible, ends up numbing and numbing.
As does the regularity of the visual rhythm.
There are a few beautiful flashes - creating images has always been a strength in Chouinard - like those hairs that get stuffy or those black fabrics that lengthen the lines.
But the choreographic approach lacks composition.
We have the impression that the choreographer, instead of going to meet Michaux's work, has prevailed, with her tics.
The result: the bodies appear flat in front of the drawings.
Michaux’s inks, like Gestalt forms, open up a broader and more pore-like imagination than dance.
Only the end, in negative, with its dancers chopped by a strobe light and the white signs in a suddenly black theater, touches the magic.
The audience liked it, the welcome was warm.
The Gymnopedies, after the intermission, is richer.
The scene is partly draped in grey, the dancers and a piano are covered with fabrics, like furniture in an abandoned house.
On the piano, dancers relay to play the scores.
Their awkwardness in music, touching, give a real fragility.
On stage, couples pass, in love duets, very sensual, even erotic.
Group work, small transition solos, moving sets, choirs, writing is less binary.
They appear, also familiar to Chouinard, wearing the red nose, in highly polarized male-female love parades.
Loves are carnage, runaway or gamblers.
The gesture, the laughter and the little cries beautifully transpose the archaic, the grace and the ridicule of the bodies in coitus, of the beings that merge.
But the play takes its real flight after salvation.
A clown comes back on stage when the audience leaves.
There, everything becomes allowed: the fourth wall falls, the explored universes overlap, the dancers cabotine, descend among the spectators, gloss, smoke, short-circuit, play codes of applause, stretch the sauce in a cleverly calculated disorder that remains sensual.
Joy and madness transpire, and it is Chouinard's art of contaminating the public.
