John Kerry admitted, unprecedentedly, that American espionage “had gone too far inappropriately.”
John Kerry noted a sharpening of the U.S. defensive attitude toward its surveillance programs by admitting, unprecedentedly, that on several occasions, espionage “had gone too far inappropriately.”
The Secretary of State also admitted that he, like Barack Obama, had ruled on “autopilot” when a series of incendiary revelations by whistleblower Edward Snowden about the NSA’s espionage activities emerged.
The leaks have put the U.S. government at the center of a diplomatic storm with its allies.
Speaking at an intergovernmental conference in London via a video link, Kerry said: “It is undeniable that the President, myself and other members of the government learned about certain things in autopilot mode because we had the opportunity, from the Second World War to the difficult years of the Cold War and then, of course, 9/11.”
He later became the first high-ranking member of the U.S. government to admit that U.S. espionage had gone beyond bounds, but insisted that everyone’s rights had not been violated.
He said, “In some cases, it went too far inappropriately.”
And the President is determined to try to clarify and make clear to the people that he is now conducting a thorough review of these practices so that no one feels mistaken.
I assure you that innocent people will not be abused in this process.
Kerry insisted, however, that the NSA was a force acting for the good and that its surveillance operations had saved many lives.
He added: “We live in a new world where people are ready to get blown up.”
There is a radical extremism in the world that is determined to try to kill people, blow them up and attack governments.
What if you could intercept their communications and stop them before they act?
We actually prevented planes from falling, buildings from exploding and people from being murdered because we were able to learn the facts in advance.
In the meantime, U.S. lawmakers will travel to Europe to address concerns about the alleged U.S. espionage case and convince Europeans of the need to continue joint counter-terrorism efforts with the United States, the chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs said on Thursday.
Senator Chris Murphy of Connecticut said he had spoken to members of the European Parliament and others this week and was concerned about the threats they had made about a possible withdrawal of anti-terrorist organizations from the National Security Agency's oversight.
“It is really important for the protection of national security in the United States that Europeans remain with us in mutual engagement in the fight against terrorism,” Murphy, a Democrat serving his first term, and chairman of the U.S. Senate’s European Affairs Subcommittee, said in an interview from Washington.
And I will go to Europe to make them understand that we must continue to work together to fight terrorism, despite the anger provoked by the NSA programs.
The press reports that the NSA has captured millions of communications in Europe, which has damaged relations with some U.S. allies, however the agency's director said this week that it was inaccurate and that it was a misunderstanding because it was about metadata that NATO allies had collected and shared with the United States.
Other revelations reported documents leaked by Snowden that the NSA intercepted data and communications from German Chancellor Angela Merkel’s mobile phone and those of 34 other heads of state.
Intelligence Director James Clapper justified spying on allies by stating that it was necessary and a common practice on both sides.
In this tumultuous atmosphere, Murphy indicated that his office was organizing a congressional trip, which is expected to take place this year, and that he hoped the delegation would include members of both parties and both chambers.
The names of the other participating legislators are expected to be revealed in the coming days.
He said the route had yet to be defined.
Murphy said the purpose of this trip was to improve relationships, but also to show “affectionate firmness.”
He explained that European heads of state must be honest with their citizens about the type of espionage programs they have been running themselves for years.
“We can modify our surveillance programs to better protect the rights of Europeans, but they also need to understand that we are not the only ones in the world to conduct espionage,” Murphy said.
Meanwhile, Kerry plans to travel to the Middle East and Poland this weekend to manage the resentment generated by US strategies in Syria, Egypt and Iran, as well as US surveillance activities.
