Australian woman appeals jail sentence in Thailand
A 21-year-old resident of Sydney, sentenced to 15 days in prison in Phuket for wrongly claiming to have been assaulted by a taxi driver, appealed the trial and was released on bail.
Stevie Rochelle Bamford was first found guilty by a Phuket Province Court on June 15 of false statements after telling Thai police that a local taxi driver, accompanied by two other men who controlled her, had assaulted her early on Sunday, June 10.
However, video surveillance recordings later revealed that she had safely returned to her hotel after separating from her Australian boyfriend.
Phuket police interviewed Bamford for two days before she confessed to inventing the story from scratch.
She was detained in a local police station cell before the court hearing.
Bamford was sentenced to 15 days in prison in a low-security detention center on the outskirts of Phuket rather than in a women’s prison.
This is the daughter of former Australian rugby league player Peter Tunks, who called the Canberra Foreign Ministry to help his daughter.
Tunks told the Sydney Sunday Telegraph that the whole family was “extremely concerned” about her daughter’s well-being and wanted her to return to Australia.
“Obviously we had a distressing time, but we hope to bring her home safely as soon as possible,” Tunks said.
Bamford appealed the judgment and was released after a bail of 50,000 baht.
In Australia, the press said that in the meantime, she was on vacation in the Krabi region of southern Thailand.
Thai judicial sources said Bamford was represented by a local lawyer from Phuket, but warned that the appeal could lead to a heavier sentence of up to two years in prison and incarceration in an adult prison.
However, following the recent Phuket killing of Michelle Smith, an Australian travel agent, Thailand could also seek to restore its deteriorating image among tourists, which could lead to an acquittal.
